05988nam a22008055i 9786155225772DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222014hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861552257727 a10.1515/97861552257722doi  a(DE-B1597)633423  a(OCoLC)1338019975  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aGN308.3.R8bE47 2013eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh03aAn Empire of Others :bCreating Ethnographic Knowledge in Imperial Russia and the USSR /ced. by Roland Cvetkovski, Alexis Hofmeister. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction: On the Making of Ethnographic Knowledge in Russia -- tImperial Case Studies: Russian and British Ethnographic Theory -- tPart I. Paradigms -- tRussian Ethnography as a Science: Truths Claimed, Trails Followed -- tBeyond, against, and with Ethnography: Physical Anthropology as a Science of Russian Modernity -- tEthnography, Marxism, and Soviet Ideology -- tEthnogenesis and Historiography: Historical Narratives for Central Asia in the 1940s and 1950s -- tPart II. Representations -- tSymbols, Conventions, and Practices: Visual Representation of Ethnographic Knowledge on Siberia in Early Modern Maps and Reports -- tEmpire Complex: Arrangements in the Russian Ethnographic Museum, 1910 -- tLearning about the Nation: Ethnographic Representations of Children, Representations of Ethnography for Children -- tPart III. Peoples -- tSiberian Ruptures: Dilemmas of Ethnography in an Imperial Situation -- tConcepts of Ukrainian Folklore and the Transition from Imperial Russia to Stalin’s Soviet Empire -- tNo Love Affair: Ingush and Chechen Imperial Ethnographies -- tNational Inventions: The Imperial Emancipation of the Karaites from Jewishness -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEthnographers helped to perceive, to understand and also to shape imperial as well as Soviet Russia's cultural diversity. This volume focuses on the contexts in which ethnographic knowledge was created. Usually, ethnographic findings were superseded by imperial discourse: Defining regions, connecting them with ethnic origins and conceiving national entities necessarily implied the mapping of political and historical hierarchies. But beyond these spatial conceptualizations the essays particularly address the specific conditions in which ethnographic knowledge appeared and changed. On the one hand, they turn to the several fields into which ethnographic knowledge poured and materialized, i.e., history, historiography, anthropology or ideology. On the other, they equally consider the impact of the specific formats, i.e., pictures, maps, atlases, lectures, songs, museums, and exhibitions, on academic as well as non-academic manifestations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aEthnologyzRussia (Federation)xHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aCentral Asia, Ethnic relations, Ethnography, Ethnology, Folklore, Historiography, History, Modernity.1 aAbashin, Sergey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlymov, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCvetkovski, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCvetkovski, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDettmering, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElfimov, Alexei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlebov, Sergey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb